----------------------- REVIEW 1 ---------------------\
PAPER: 14\
TITLE: What is the Value of an Action in Ice Hockey? Q-Learning for the NHL\
AUTHORS: Oliver Schulte, Zeyu Zhao and Kurt Routley\
\
OVERALL EVALUATION: 1 (weak accept)\
\
----------- REVIEW -----------\
I\'92ve found this to be an interesting application and, to the best of my knowledge, a new area of research within the hockey analytics scope. \'a0The closest research that I know of would be by a Carleton University graduate student named Alex Diaz who has looked at association rules and data mining within hockey, from play by play data. \'a0The use of markov rules to identify the better goal scorers is interesting.\
\
A few things I\'92ve noted and you may wish to consider if you want to continue this research.\
\
One area the research lacks is that inclusion of any modern hockey analytics research or analytics statistics. \'a0Modern hockey statistic research does not move through traditional academia circles but rather on the internet where the research community is very active in blogs and Twitter with their publishing. \'a0\
\
Real-time data is known to be affected by rink biasses where certain areas are known to under/over count statistics (hits, shots attempts) due to human biases (nothing malicious). \'a0Players who have these areas as their home arena will spend half their careers in one area could artificially look better or worse than they are. \'a0This might wash out over multiple seasons but it is worth considering looking at only away games for each player, or adjusting for the rink biases similar to War-on-Ice.\
\
Another field to consider is that goal scoring is a relatively rare event on the ice compared to shot attempts. \'a0PDO (statistic of luck of a player which is the summation of on-ice shooting percentage and save-percentage) can swing wildly between years in extreme cases. \'a0The hockey analytics field prefers to look at shot-attempts for and against to create possession statistics which has shown to be better predictors of future goals than previous goal data. \'a0It could be valuable to use this to predict future shots than future goals. \'a0\
\
Penalties are encoded as a negative value towards player, but a penalty is not always negative. \'a0Receiving a penalty for preventing an odd-man rush or breakaway on your goaltender reduces the chance of a goal against compared to a 5 on 4.\
\
Hockey analytics often uses an \'93eye test\'94 when creating new statistics to show who are better players. \'a0There are players who are well known by the quantitative and qualitative hockey communities who if are not in the top of the results, it should be questioned how accurate the results are. \'a0The previous work this paper touches on (THoR) suggers from this as the authors suggested that Tyler Kennedy was one of the better players. \'a0This immediately caused questioning from the hockey analytics community.\
\
When I see a lack of the two most well known goal scorers in the NHL (Steve Stamkos and Alex Ovechkin - by varying hockey scoring studies and statistics) I have similar doubts. \'a0There are some good scorers in the results being generated, but not the best ones. \'a0It also seems to have difficulty identifying young players who are near their physical peak and are scoring at a more efficient rate (Goals/60) than older players but lack the ice time from their coaches yet.\
\
Comparing the results to the +/- of a player is not ideal. \'a0+/- has shown to hold little weight in the value of a player given how it is counted and under what circumstances. \'a0Better statistics to compare it to might be possession (Corsi, Fenwick, Scoring Chance %) or to relative possession data. \
\
Similarly, comparing scoring value vs salary can be arbitrary depending when the player was signed. \'a0Backdiving contracts can hide true value of players and a player signed for $9Million a year in 2006 under a 55M Cap vs $9M in 2014 under a 70M cap have different weights.\
\
