----------------------- REVIEW 2 ---------------------\
PAPER: 14\
TITLE: What is the Value of an Action in Ice Hockey? Q-Learning for the NHL\
AUTHORS: Oliver Schulte, Zeyu Zhao and Kurt Routley\
\
OVERALL EVALUATION: 3 (strong accept)\
\
----------- REVIEW -----------\
This is a nice paper, very well suited for this workshop. \'a0The idea of applying on policy reinforcement learning starting from actual game sequences is very simple yet elegant. \'a0The technique is very timely as more and more precise data is being logged in major sports. \'a0I like the overview of related work, although I can not say anything about its completeness. \'a0The idea is so elegant and the results so promising that I am actually surprised nobody has done this before. The authors also show that the technique makes sense and produces very useable ratings of actions and players as a consequence.\
\
Overall, the write up is nice, well executed, except for a few discrepancies that seem to have been caused by deadline surfing. \'a0For example, it is unclear why INTRODUCTION is written using all caps. \'a0Another is the slightly weird formatting of the motivation subsection of the introduction. \'a0Also, just to let you know, I had difficulties printing the paper. \'a0i don't know if this was caused locally, but printing failed on page 5, possible because of the figure?\
\
The use of "Q-learning in the on-policy setting" is a bit weird. \'a0Yes, you are learning q-values, and yes, in an on-policy setting, but Q-learning is the name of an off-policy reinforcement learning algorithm, specifically. \'a0You could replace "Q-learning" with "Q-value learning" if you want to keep the sentence.\
\
It would be nice to see a comparison of how the techniques is specific to ice hockey, even if only qualitatively. \'a0I for one assume that ice-hockey (as a complete layman) assume the technique to fit ice-hockey so well because of team size and game-speed. \'a0Compared to for example soccer, defenders will have lower q-values connected to pretty much all of their actions relative to forwards, as they are less likely to score or give an assist? \'a0It would be nice to have the authors comment on this difference.\
\
