----------------------- REVIEW 3 ---------------------\
PAPER: 14\
TITLE: What is the Value of an Action in Ice Hockey? Q-Learning for the NHL\
AUTHORS: Oliver Schulte, Zeyu Zhao and Kurt Routley\
\
OVERALL EVALUATION: 3 (strong accept)\
\
----------- REVIEW -----------\
The authors present an attempt to assess player values in the NFL using data from play by play descriptions to attempt to infer the values of indirect actions. \'a0To perform these estimates the authors make use of a Q learning framework to employ Markov games where the actions are play by play occurrences and are associate with a team.\
\
The authors indicate that their results suggest there are cross season correlations of results, especially with respect to goal scoring, which is what you would hope for a model of performance. \'a0The authors also show results estimating the individual impacts of players that seem reasonable (at least from someone with some knowledge of player performance), and show the limitations of current methods such as +/- estimates.\
\
It would be interesting to follow up on these results with studies to determine if the results carryover in useful ways. \'a0For example, the authors could look at players who change teams and look at the effect of changing teams on things like +/- scores that are based partly on the team and see if the results that one would predict from the RL value of players predicts changes to these values.\
\
I would like to see more analysis of the results in any case, the paper seems somewhat preliminary at this point. \'a0But the authors should also be commended for making so much data available to other researchers. \'a0This is a significant additional contribution of the paper.\
\
